crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The analyzed ELF binary is a standard PyInstaller bootloader for Linux. Its primary function is to serve as a self-extracting wrapper for a bundled Python application. Key behaviors observed in the decompilation include: 1) Identification and extraction of an embedded PKG archive from the executable itself (using /proc/self/exe and zlib/inflate decompression in sub_4025c0 and sub_402db0); 2) Creation of temporary runtime directories (typically /tmp/_MEIXXXXXX via mkdtemp); 3) Dynamic resolution of Python and Tcl/Tk shared library symbols via dlopen/dlsym (sub_405860 and sub_4071f0); and 4) Forking and execution of the extracted Python interpreter and scripts (sub_4081c0). Relevant IOCs include PyInstaller-specific environment variables (_PYI_ARCHIVE_FILE, _PYI_APPLICATION_HOME_DIR) and diagnostic strings confirming its role as a PyInstaller loader. While often used to package malware, the bootloader's logic here is consistent with legitimate tool use.
